The shrine has long received strong patronage from successive rulers, and it is said that during the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|Sengoku period}} it possessed shrine domains covering 700 {{ill|Town (unit)|ja|町}} ({{ill|Shrine domain|ja|寺社領}}). During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代}}, it held 20 koku of {{ill|Shuin land|ja|朱印地・黒印地|lt=Red Seal Land|lt_ja=朱印領}}, and the "Kōzaki Shrine Documents"—a collection of ancient manuscripts and illustrations passed down from the early {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代}} to the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代}}—is considered an extremely important historical source of the {{ill|Medieval|ja|中世}} period ({{ill|Historical source|ja|史料}}), having been designated as a tangible cultural property (ancient documents) of Chiba Prefecture ({{ill|Tangible Cultural Property (Ancient Documents) of Chiba Prefecture|ja|千葉県指定文化財一覧#古文書|lt=Chiba Prefecture Tangible Cultural Property (Ancient Documents)|lt_ja=千葉県の有形文化財（古文書）}}). Furthermore, the "Jinguji Documents" held by the former head temple ({{ill|Head temple|ja|別当寺}}) {{ill|Jinguji|ja|神宮寺 (千葉県神崎町)|lt=Jinguji|lt_ja=神宮寺}}, despite missing 60 out of 600 volumes of the {{ill|Mahaprajnaparamita Sutra|ja|大般若波羅蜜多経}}, are highly valued as a sutra transcription from the {{ill|Nanboku-chō period|ja|南北朝時代 (日本)|lt=Nanboku-chō period|lt_ja=南北朝期}}. The colophon ({{ill|Colophon|ja|奥書}}) reveals details about the temples ({{ill|Temple|ja|寺院}}), monks ({{ill|Monk|ja|僧侶}}), and the sphere of religious influence at that time, and it has also been designated as a tangible cultural property of Chiba Prefecture ({{ill|Tangible Cultural Property of Chiba Prefecture|ja|千葉県指定文化財一覧#古文書|lt=Chiba Prefecture Tangible Cultural Property|lt_ja=千葉県の有形文化財}}).

== Transportation ==
* About a 20‐minute walk from {{ill|Narita Line|ja|成田線}}{{ill|Shimōsa-Kozaki Station|ja|下総神崎駅}}
* Near the south end of Kozaki Ōhashi on {{ill|National Route 356|ja|国道356号}} and {{ill|Ibaraki and Chiba Prefectural Road 107, Edosaki-Kozaki Line|ja|茨城県道・千葉県道107号江戸崎神崎線}}

