'''Kōzaki Shrine''' (神崎神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto shrine|qq=}} located in {{ill|Chiba Prefecture|ja|千葉県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chiba Prefecture|qq=}}{{ill|Katori District|ja|香取郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Katori District|qq=}}{{ill|Kozaki Town|ja|神崎町|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kozaki Town|qq=}} ({{ill|Shimōsa Province|ja|下総国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimōsa Province|qq=}}{{ill|Katori District|ja|香取郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Katori District|qq=}}). Its former {{ill|Shrine Rank|ja|社格|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shrine Rank|qq=}} was defined under the {{ill|Modern Shrine Ranking System|ja|近代社格制度#諸社|lt=Prefectural shrine|lt_ja=県社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Modern Shrine Ranking System|qq=}}.

It enshrines as its main deities {{ill|Tennichibune no Mikoto|ja|天鳥船命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tennichibune no Mikoto|qq=}}, {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主|lt=Ōkuninushi no Mikoto|lt_ja=大己貴命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōkuninushi|qq=}}, and {{ill|Sukunahikona|ja|スクナビコナ|1=Sukunabikona|lt=Sukunahikona no Mikoto|lt_ja=少彦名命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sukunahikona|qq=}}.

== Overview ==
The founding date of this shrine is unknown, but according to its tradition, it is said that in the 2nd year of the {{ill|Hakuhō|ja|白鳳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakuhō|qq=}} era ({{ill|673|ja|673|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/673|qq=}}) it was relocated to this site from the two mounds at Ōura Pond, located on the border between {{ill|Hitachi Province|ja|常陸国|lt=Hitachi|lt_ja=常陸|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hitachi Province|qq=}} and Shimōsa. Until the {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}} period, it was known as "Komatsu Shrine", but in the 3rd year of the {{ill|Genkei|ja|元慶|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Genkei|qq=}} era ({{ill|879|ja|879|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/879|qq=}}) it was conferred the lower Junior Fifth Rank ({{ill|Junior Fifth Rank|ja|従五位|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Fifth Rank|qq=}}下) in the {{ill|Shinto Ranking system|ja|神階|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto Ranking system|qq=}}.<ref>In the ''{{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|qq=}}'', in the entry for April 5 in the 3rd year of the Genkei era, it is recorded: "To the {{ill|Mihosu Shrine|ja|御穂神社|lt=Miryōjin|lt_ja=御廊神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mihosu Shrine|qq=}} of Suruga Province with the upper Junior Fifth Rank, the lower Senior Fifth Rank is conferred, and to the Komatsu Shrine of Shimōsa Province with the upper Sixth Rank, the lower Junior Fifth Rank is conferred."</ref>

This shrine is not an auxiliary shrine ({{ill|Auxiliary shrine|ja|末社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Auxiliary shrine|qq=}}) of {{ill|Katori Shrine|ja|香取神宮|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Katori Shrine|qq=}}, but during the periodic rebuilding it played a regular role in constructing the "Asame Hall". Furthermore, according to the ''{{ill|Tone River Illustrated History|ja|利根川図志|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tone River Illustrated History|qq=}}'', this shrine was once part of the former territory of a chief priestly family, and its enshrined deity, {{ill|Tennichibune no Mikoto|ja|天鳥船命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tennichibune no Mikoto|qq=}}, is regarded as the messenger dispatched under the command of {{ill|Kotoshironushi|ja|事代主神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotoshironushi|qq=}} when {{ill|Keizutsushi no Kami|ja|経津主神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Keizutsushi no Kami|qq=}} of {{ill|Katori Shrine|ja|香取神宮|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Katori Shrine|qq=}} and {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|鹿島神宮|lt=Takemikazuchi no Kami|lt_ja=武甕槌神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takemikazuchi|qq=}} of {{ill|Kashima Shrine|ja|鹿島神宮|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kashima Shrine|qq=}} negotiated the {{ill|Land Concession|ja|葦原中国平定|lt=transfer of sovereignty|lt_ja=国譲り|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Land Concession|qq=}} with Ōkuninushi. It is also noted that the Tennichibune, a ship upon which deities ride ({{ill|Ship|ja|諸手船|lt=Various-hand ship|lt_ja=船|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ship|qq=}}), is alternatively known as Tori no Ishikusu-fune no Kami, while this shrine possesses a large {{ill|Kusunoki|ja|クスノキ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kusunoki|qq=}}, commonly called the {{ill|Nanjamonja|ja|ナンジャモンジャ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nanjamonja|qq=}} tree.<ref>{{ill|Mito Kōmon|ja|水戸黄門|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mito Kōmon|qq=}} is said to have once pondered, "What on earth is the name of this tree?" Although he did not actually travel throughout Japan, he is known to have visited this shrine.</ref> The main tree is surrounded by five saplings; its trunk has a circumference of 13.1 meters and a height of 19 meters, and it is designated as a national {{ill|Natural Monument|ja|天然記念物|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Natural Monument|qq=}} under the name {{ill|Great Kozaki Kusunoki|ja|神崎の大クス|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Great Kozaki Kusunoki|qq=}}. The shrine grove, known as the "Kozaki Forest", is designated as a natural monument of Chiba Prefecture ({{ill|Natural Monuments of Chiba Prefecture|ja|千葉県指定文化財一覧#天然記念物|lt=Chiba Prefecture Natural Monuments|lt_ja=千葉県の天然記念物|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Natural Monuments of Chiba Prefecture|qq=}}).

[[File:Kōzaki-jinja_(Kōzaki,_Chiba)_12.jpg|thumb|right|230px|{{ill|Great Kozaki Kusunoki|ja|神崎の大クス|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Great Kozaki Kusunoki|qq=}}. Commonly known as the Nanjamonja tree.]]

The shrine has long received strong patronage from successive rulers, and it is said that during the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|Sengoku period|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sengoku period|qq=}} it possessed shrine domains covering 700 {{ill|Town (unit)|ja|町|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Town (unit)|qq=}} ({{ill|Shrine domain|ja|寺社領|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shrine domain|qq=}}). During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo period|qq=}}, it held 20 koku of {{ill|Shuin land|ja|朱印地・黒印地|lt=Red Seal Land|lt_ja=朱印領|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shuin land|qq=}}, and the "Kōzaki Shrine Documents"—a collection of ancient manuscripts and illustrations passed down from the early {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamakura period|qq=}} to the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Muromachi period|qq=}}—is considered an extremely important historical source of the {{ill|Medieval|ja|中世|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Medieval|qq=}} period ({{ill|Historical source|ja|史料|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Historical source|qq=}}), having been designated as a tangible cultural property (ancient documents) of Chiba Prefecture ({{ill|Tangible Cultural Property (Ancient Documents) of Chiba Prefecture|ja|千葉県指定文化財一覧#古文書|lt=Chiba Prefecture Tangible Cultural Property (Ancient Documents)|lt_ja=千葉県の有形文化財（古文書）|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tangible Cultural Property (Ancient Documents) of Chiba Prefecture|qq=}}). Furthermore, the "Jinguji Documents" held by the former head temple ({{ill|Head temple|ja|別当寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Head temple|qq=}}) {{ill|Jinguji|ja|神宮寺 (千葉県神崎町)|lt=Jinguji|lt_ja=神宮寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jinguji|qq=}}, despite missing 60 out of 600 volumes of the {{ill|Mahaprajnaparamita Sutra|ja|大般若波羅蜜多経|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mahaprajnaparamita Sutra|qq=}}, are highly valued as a sutra transcription from the {{ill|Nanboku-chō period|ja|南北朝時代 (日本)|lt=Nanboku-chō period|lt_ja=南北朝期|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nanboku-chō period|qq=}}. The colophon ({{ill|Colophon|ja|奥書|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Colophon|qq=}}) reveals details about the temples ({{ill|Temple|ja|寺院|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Temple|qq=}}), monks ({{ill|Monk|ja|僧侶|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Monk|qq=}}), and the sphere of religious influence at that time, and it has also been designated as a tangible cultural property of Chiba Prefecture ({{ill|Tangible Cultural Property of Chiba Prefecture|ja|千葉県指定文化財一覧#古文書|lt=Chiba Prefecture Tangible Cultural Property|lt_ja=千葉県の有形文化財|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tangible Cultural Property of Chiba Prefecture|qq=}}).

== Transportation ==
